{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526975"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:28:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:28:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14186"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14186","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14186"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.14,0.5,0.16,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6869"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112969"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6869","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6869"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14186"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95001"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1175"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3003"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15647"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43500"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44309"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46478"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112969"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of fatigue, confusion, and easy bruising. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. She has scattered petechiae on her arms and legs. Neurological examination reveals mild confusion but no focal deficits. Investigations reveal haemoglobin 80 g/L (115-155), platelet count 15 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400), creatinine 280 \u03bcmol/L (45-90), and ADAMTS13 activity \u0026lt;5% (60-130).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following sets of investigation results would you expect to see in this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haemoglobin normal, platelets low, schistocytes on blood film, direct antiglobulin test positive","Haemoglobin low, platelets low, spherocytes on blood film, direct antiglobulin test negative","Haemoglobin low, platelets low, schistocytes on blood film, direct antiglobulin test negative","Haemoglobin low, bite cells on blood film, direct antiglobulin test negative","Haemoglobin normal, platelets low, bite cells on blood film, direct antiglobulin test positive"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP), a life-threatening condition characterised by microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, and organ dysfunction. The severely reduced ADAMTS13 activity (\u0026lt;5%) is diagnostic for TTP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin low, platelets low, schistocytes on blood film, direct antiglobulin test negative\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct set of investigation results expected in TTP. The low haemoglobin is due to microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, while low platelets result from consumption in microthrombi. Schistocytes (fragmented red blood cells) are seen on the blood film due to mechanical damage as they pass through partially occluded small vessels. The direct antiglobulin test (DAT) is typically negative as the haemolysis is not immune-mediated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin normal, platelets low, schistocytes on blood film, direct antiglobulin test positive\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While TTP does cause thrombocytopenia and schistocytes, the haemoglobin should be low due to haemolysis, and the DAT should be negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin low, platelets low, spherocytes on blood film, direct antiglobulin test negative\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While the haemoglobin and platelet counts are consistent with TTP, spherocytes are characteristic of hereditary spherocytosis or autoimmune haemolytic anaemia, not the mechanical haemolysis seen in TTP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin low, bite cells on blood film, and a negative direct antiglobulin test\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. This would be consistent with oxidative haemolysis (e.g., glucose-6-phosphate dehydrogenase deficiency), which is non-immune. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemoglobin normal, platelets low, bite cells on blood film, direct antiglobulin test positive\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it does not match the haematological profile of TTP. The haemoglobin should be low, schistocytes rather than bite cells should be present, and the DAT should be negative.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn TTP, the severe deficiency of ADAMTS13 (typically \u0026lt;10% of normal activity) leads to accumulation of ultra-large von Willebrand factor multimers. These cause spontaneous platelet aggregation and microvascular thrombosis, resulting in the characteristic clinical and laboratory findings. Prompt recognition and treatment with plasma exchange is crucial, as it replenishes ADAMTS13 and removes autoantibodies, significantly improving outcomes in this potentially fatal condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP) is characterised by severe ADAMTS13 deficiency, typically \u003C10% of normal activity.","TTP presents with microangiopathic haemolytic anaemia, thrombocytopenia, and organ dysfunction, with schistocytes on blood film.","The direct antiglobulin test is negative in TTP as the haemolysis is mechanical rather than immune-mediated."],"references":["Joly BS, Coppo P, Veyradier A. Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura. Blood. 2017 Apr 17;129(21):2836\u201346. Available at: https://ashpublications.org/blood/article/129/21/2836/36273/Thrombotic-thrombocytopenic-purpura"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95001"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14186"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95001"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T17:21:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T17:22:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6869"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112969"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags